fields.history_note:
rules sheet of pink paper also gives notes and prices of other games publisher by Ogilvy.
see also price sheet E. 801-1945.

David Ogilvy was at the address from about 1835 to 1847.

Equipment required: 1 card, hand coloured lithograph showing soldier and his dog
37 cards lithographed with the titles of various parts of a soldier's uniform, groups of animals, eg Thirteen Dromedaries, and seemingly unrelated methods of transport and locations.
11 cards with hand coloured lithographs of other items.
16 bone counters (red, yellow, green, blue) diam 9/16in.

Rules:
THE MERRY ROUND GAME OF THE POOR OLD SOLDIER & HIS DOG
DIRECTIONS FOR PLAYING THE GAME.

1.  The first step will be to deliver counters inthe usual manner - say 6 white and two red counters to each player; one red counter to be considered equal in value to 12 white counters.
2.  Any number may player:  the dealer must put six white counters into the pool.
3.  The dealer, after shuffling the cards and letting them be cut by the player on his right hand, must deliver three cards to each player with their faces downwards, which are not to be looked at until it is each player's turn to play.  If more than ten persons play, two cards only must be dealt round; the large card of the Poor Solider is to be placed in the middle of the table next to the pool.
4.  The player next to the dealer on the left hand then must turn up a card: if the printing on it describes any thing than can be worn on the person of the Old Soldier, that card must be thrown on the large picture card, and the play may take one white counter from the pool; the other cards with printing on them must each pay one counter to the pool.
5.  The other losing and winning cards, the the number of counters, to be taken from and put into the pool are described on each card.
6.  The Full Purse is the game, and the person playing it may take the pool; but probably two or more deals may be made before it is delivered to any of the players.
7.  The cards must be turned up in regular succession; should not the Game Card be amongst them untill all are played, then a fresh deal must be made by the player next on the left hand and the pool dressed in similar manner as by the first dealer, and so on all round the table while the parties continue to play.
8.  All the holders of cards not turned up when the Game is taken must each of them pay one white counter to the pool, which are to be in addition to the counters put in by the next dealer.
9.  A variation of this game may be made by the players buying or selling their cards previous to turning them up.
